<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Turn your plan into a public piece, without hiding the trade-off to do it.</p>
  <p>Your plan has been a document for an audience of one teacher. Today it becomes something a stranger can learn from. You build two public-facing things. The first is a <strong>live activity</strong> for the school's environmental showcase that teaches other students the choice your neighborhood faces. The framing matters: not "here is my plan," but "here is the trade-off this place has to make, what would you choose?" The second is a <strong>shareable artifact</strong>, a map-based infographic, a carousel, or a short captioned video, that carries the same message to people who never visited your station.</p>
  <p>Here is the design tension this block is built around, and you should name it out loud. Public outreach rewards a clean, confident message: one big idea, no caveats, easy to share. The rubric rewards the opposite: naming what you sacrificed. If you let the public format win, your artifact becomes a slogan ("greener, fairer, flood-proof") that quietly erases the trade-off you worked so hard to make honest in Block 5. So the discipline today is to build a public piece that is clear <em>and</em> still shows the cost. The strongest artifacts make the trade-off the message: "to make this neighborhood walkable, we gave up X, and here is why we think that is worth it."</p>
  <p>Two practical things, because this goes public. Your shareable artifact will be posted through a <strong>student takeover of the school's Instagram account</strong> for this unit, so it reaches a real audience well beyond the showcase. Because it lands on a public account, anything that names or shows real people needs <strong>consent</strong>, with an <strong>opt-out</strong>, and there is always a <strong>non-public fallback</strong> (you can present and submit without anything being posted). Design the piece so it works either way, and keep the people in it comfortable.</p>
  <p class="sub" style="color: var(--muted);">Build the artifact so it stands on its own at the showcase and also reads well as a post on the school's Instagram.</p>
</section>

