<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All four paths end with a public activity and a shareable artifact that communicate clearly while still showing the trade-off.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I have a public activity and a shareable artifact that make my plan clear to a stranger and still show what it gave up, with a consent and fallback plan in place.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Draft the activity and artifact (default)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Build the live activity (the choice you put in front of visitors) and the shareable artifact (the map-infographic, carousel, or short video). Make the trade-off the message in both, not a footnote.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Test the message on a fresh peer (stretch)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Show your artifact to a peer who has not seen your plan. Ask them to tell you what the neighborhood gained and what it gave up. If they can only name the gain, your message is hiding the trade-off. Revise until both come through.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Consent and fallback plan (choice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Sort the public-facing logistics: who appears in or is named by your piece, what gets shown where, who needs to agree, and your non-public fallback if anyone opts out. A piece that cannot run without exposing someone is not ready.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Peer-help — is my message hiding the trade-off (practice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If you are not sure whether your piece flattened into a slogan, come to the peer-help table. Read each other's one-line message and name the trade-off it hides, then fix yours.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="block-section show">
  <span class="section-tag">Show</span>
  <h2>What you're submitting today</h2>
  <p class="sub">A draft activity and a draft artifact, with the trade-off visible in both, plus your consent and fallback choice.</p>
  <div class="submission-callout">
    <div class="label">Draft public piece + consent plan</div>
    <p>Three things: (1) a draft of your live activity (the choice you put to visitors), (2) a draft of your shareable artifact, with the trade-off visible in each (to get this, we gave up that), and (3) your consent and fallback note (who appears, what gets posted where, the non-public option). A piece that only shows the win is not ready, however polished.</p>
    <a href="#" class="rubric-link">Submit via Google Classroom →</a>
  </div>
  <p class="rubric-meta">
    <strong>Rubric link:</strong> the public-artifact guardrail on the <a href="/units/unit-6/assessment-sustainable-neighborhood-plan/">Sustainable Neighborhood Plan</a> says the public piece must show the trade-off, not hide it. A clean slogan that erases the sacrifice undercuts the Thinking and Transfer gate even when the Communication looks strong. See the <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">rubric</a>.
  </p>
</section>

